al reading experience, open data, and open-source tools.</span></span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="sc-ctuRtO cEtLrF"><div class="sc-dpRLZP eaVTzC">Why is it called READr?<div class="sc-bgnbwU brHWjP">+</div></div><div class="sc-ccJWcV heVDFr"><div class="DraftEditor-root"><div class="DraftEditor-editorContainer"><div class="public-DraftEditor-content" contenteditable="false" spellcheck="false" style="outline:none;user-select:text;-webkit-user-select:text;white-space:pre-wrap;word-wrap:break-word"><div data-contents="true"><div class="" data-block="true" data-editor="204bi" data-offset-key="eh9vb-0-0"><div data-offset-key="eh9vb-0-0" class="public-DraftStyleDefault-block public-DraftStyleDefault-ltr"><span data-offset-key="eh9vb-0-0"><span data-text="true">The name READr comes from the combination of our team members and goals, which is to bring together people from different backgrounds to create news: Reporter, Engineer, Audience, and Designer.</span></span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="sc-ctuRtO cEtLrF"><div class="sc-dpRLZP eaVTzC">Why does READr specialize in data journalism?<div class="sc-bgnbwU brHWjP">+</div></div><div class="sc-ccJWcV heVDFr"><div class="DraftEditor-root"><div class="DraftEditor-editorContainer"><div class="public-DraftEditor-content" contenteditable="false" spellcheck="false" style="outline:none;user-select:text;-webkit-user-select:text;white-space:pre-wrap;word-wrap:break-word"><div data-contents="true"><div class="" data-block="true" data-editor="6sdp6" data-offset-key="eh9vb-0-0"><div data-offset-key="eh9vb-0-0" class="public-DraftStyleDefault-block public-DraftStyleDefault-ltr"><span data-offset-key="eh9vb-0-0"><span data-text="true">We found that our colleagues often bring different problem awareness and perspectives, making the topic more diverse. Sometimes it&#x27;s the engineer who comes up with the web presentation that perfectly hits the core of the news, and sometimes it&#x27;s the designer who suggests visual interactive methods. The production process is not limited by the framework of &quot;news,&quot; which makes the news more interesting. But who says news can only have one face?</span></span></div></div><div class="" data-block="true" data-editor="6sdp6" data-offset-key="1sdn-0-0"><div data-offset-key="1sdn-0-0" class="public-DraftStyleDefault-block public-DraftStyleDefault-ltr"><span data-offset-key="1sdn-0-0"><span data-text="true">So, can the content of news only be determined by the traditional editorial board? What would happen if readers were involved in news production? If the door is opened to readers with various expertise during news production, would the topics be more attractive? Can &quot;open newsroom&quot; no longer be just a slogan?</span></span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div>
